rbvs

Class Order

  • java.lang.Object
    • rbvs.record.Record
      • rbvs.Order
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    IDeepCopy, IRecord

    public class Order
extends Record
implements IDeepCopy
    An Order is a specific type of Record. It has an identifier, is associated with a Table and contains a list of IProducts. In essence, it states what products have been ordered at a specific table. Furthermore, an Order has a status that indicates in which state the order currently is. Possibly values are specified in OrderState.

    Attributes of the class:

    • Table associated with the Order.
    • List of IProducts
    • The current state represented by an OrderState

        public boolean setState(OrderState newStatus)
        Sets the state of the order record.

        The state can only be modified if the order is neither paid nor cancelled. If the order is changed the method returns true; in any other case false.

        Parameters:
        newStatus - the new state
        Returns:

      • deepCopy

        public Order deepCopy()
        Creates and returns a copy of this object by either invoking a private copy constructor, or by creating a new object of the same class and setting its values accordingly. The precise meaning of "copy" may depend on the class of the object. The general intent is that, for any object x, the expression: 
         x.deepCopy() != x
        will be true, and that the expression: 
         x.deepCopy().getClass() == x.getClass()
        will be true, but these are not absolute requirements.

        While it is typically the case that: 

         x.deepCopy().equals(x)
        will be true, this is not an absolute requirement.

        NOTE: Keep in mind that for all referenced IProducts in this Order, e.g. the elements of the private Collection, a copy has to be created as well.

        Specified by:
        deepCopy in interface IDeepCopy
        Returns:
        a clone of this object

      • equals

        public boolean equals(Object obj)
        An Order is equal to an object if it has the same class and all of its attributes match.

        In case of the referenced IProducts it is checked whether all of them are contained in the object to be compared and vice versa. This means that the intersection of both sets returns the same set of IProducts that is contained in the original lists.

        A intersect B = B intersect A = A = B

        equals in class Object
